Selecting a Subgroup in Shiny
Inside Shiny, switch the active subgroup programmatically with split_tabviz_select():
observeEvent(input$region, {
  split_tabviz_select(split_tabviz_proxy("split_plot"), input$region)
})
See Shiny Integration for the full pattern.

Tooltips
Tooltips are opt-in. Specify the column names you want to surface on marker hover:


Code
data(glp1_trials)

glp1_trials |&gt;
  filter(row_type == "data", group == "Main Trials") |&gt;
  head(4) |&gt;
  tabviz(label = "study",
    interaction = web_interaction(tooltip_fields = c("n", "events", "pvalue")),
    footnote = "Hover over markers to see tooltip",
    columns = list(
      viz_forest(point = "hr", lower = "lower", upper = "upper",
                 scale = "log", null_value = 1)
    )
  )






See Interactivity for the full set of web_interaction() controls.

Customizing Group Headers
Control the visual styling of group headers at each level using theme modifiers:


Code
custom_theme &lt;- web_theme_cochrane() |&gt;
  set_theme_field(c("row_group", "L1", "bg"),            "#E0F2FE") |&gt;
  set_theme_field(c("row_group", "L1", "text", "size"),  "1.1rem") |&gt;
  set_theme_field(c("row_group", "L1", "text", "weight"), 700) |&gt;
  set_theme_field(c("row_group", "L2", "bg"),            "#F0F9FF") |&gt;
  set_theme_field(c("row_group", "L2", "text", "italic"), TRUE) |&gt;
  set_theme_field(c("row_group", "L2", "text", "size"),  "0.95rem") |&gt;
  set_spacing(indent_per_level = 20)

tabviz(hierarchical_data,
  label = "study",
  group = c("region", "country"),
  columns = list(
    viz_forest(point = "or", lower = "lower", upper = "upper",
               scale = "log", null_value = 1)
  ),
  theme = custom_theme
)


The row_group cluster is one of the v2 theme’s Tier 3 component clusters. Its three tiers — L1 (outermost), L2, L3 — each carry bg, fg, rule, text (a TextRole bundle: family / size / weight / italic), and border_bottom. See Themes guide for the full structure and Themes Reference for the class definitions.

Shiny / proxy patterns
The proxy verbs below mutate the live widget without a re-render — scroll position, open/closed groups, and selection survive.

Switch themes mid-session without a re-render


Code
server &lt;- function(input, output, session) {
  output$plot &lt;- renderTabviz({
    tabviz(data, label = "study",
           columns = list(viz_forest(point = "hr", lower = "lower", upper = "upper",
                                     null_value = 1, scale = "log")))
  })

  observeEvent(input$theme, {
    tabviz_proxy("plot") |&gt; set_theme(input$theme)
  })
}




Filter rows from a slider
Proxy-dispatched filter_rows() updates in place. clear_filters() first to drop any earlier filter rather than stack on top of it.


Code
ui &lt;- fluidPage(
  sliderInput("max_p", "Max p-value", min = 0, max = 1, value = 0.1),
  tabvizOutput("plot")
)

server &lt;- function(input, output, session) {
  output$plot &lt;- renderTabviz({ tabviz(data, ...) })

  observeEvent(input$max_p, {
    tabviz_proxy("plot") |&gt;
      clear_filters() |&gt;
      filter_rows("pval", "lt", input$max_p)
  })
}




Change a column’s header or width mid-session


Code
observeEvent(input$relabel, {
  tabviz_proxy("plot") |&gt;
    update_column("hr", header = "Hazard Ratio", width = 160)
})




Preserve scroll and selection across updates
Proxy verbs preserve UI state; renderTabviz({ tabviz(...) }) re-renders the whole widget and resets it. Reach for the proxy whenever the change is incremental.


Code
# GOOD: incremental update keeps scroll/selection
observeEvent(input$sort_col, {
  tabviz_proxy("plot") |&gt; sort_rows(input$sort_col, "desc")
})

# BAD: full re-render loses scroll position
output$plot &lt;- renderTabviz({
  data |&gt;
    arrange(desc(.data[[input$sort_col]])) |&gt;
    tabviz(...)
})

Multiple effects (forest)
tabviz(data, label = "study", columns = list(
  viz_forest(
    effects = list(
      effect_forest("itt_hr", "itt_lo", "itt_hi", label = "ITT", color = "#2563eb"),
      effect_forest("pp_hr",  "pp_lo",  "pp_hi",  label = "Per-Protocol", color = "#16a34a")
    ),
    scale = "log", null_value = 1
  )
))

Where the version lives
Every WebSpec and SplitForestPayload that R serializes carries an explicit version field at the top level:
{
  version: "1.0",
  data: { ... },
  columns: [ ... ],
  // ...
}
The string is parsed JS-side by parseSpecVersion in srcjs/src/spec/index.ts. Both htmlwidget bindings validate on every renderValue; the SplitForestPayload validator runs the same check.
Sources of truth: - R side: WIRE_FORMAT_VERSION in R/wire-version.R (single constant) - JS side: CURRENT_VERSION in srcjs/src/spec/index.ts - A doc-test in tests/testthat/test-wire-version.R reads both files and asserts they agree.

The prototype
The spike extracted the source-tagging slice (~22 lines of state + helpers + ~50 markSource() call sites scattered through the store).

Slice file (srcjs/src/stores/slices/source.svelte.ts)
export type SourceTag = "user" | "proxy";

export interface SourceSlice {
  markSource: (field: string) =&gt; void;
  withSource: &lt;T&gt;(src: SourceTag, fn: () =&gt; T) =&gt; T;
  getSource: (field: string) =&gt; SourceTag;
}

export function createSourceSlice(): SourceSlice {
  let currentSource: SourceTag = "user";
  const lastSource = $state&lt;Record&lt;string, SourceTag&gt;&gt;({});

  function markSource(field: string): void {
    lastSource[field] = currentSource;
  }

  function withSource&lt;T&gt;(src: SourceTag, fn: () =&gt; T): T {
    const prev = currentSource;
    currentSource = src;
    try { return fn(); } finally { currentSource = prev; }
  }

  function getSource(field: string): SourceTag {
    return lastSource[field] ?? "user";
  }

  return { markSource, withSource, getSource };
}
Notable points:

currentSource stays a plain let (no $state). Its mutations are synchronous and don’t need to drive reactivity; only lastSource is observed externally.
The slice is self-contained: nothing else needs to know how source tagging is implemented.
The exported interface (SourceSlice) is what the rest of the store depends on; the implementation behind it is the slice’s business.



Wiring in the main store
In createForestStore():
const source = createSourceSlice();
const markSource = source.markSource;
const withSource = source.withSource;
// ... ~50 existing call sites work unchanged
The local const markSource = source.markSource aliasing keeps the existing ~50 markSource("...") call sites scattered through the store unchanged. Minimal-delta migration for an existing module; new modules from here on can just use source.markSource(...) directly.
In the public-API return:
return {
  // ...
  getSource: source.getSource,
  withSource,
  // ...
};

Shiny wire format
Each event becomes one Shiny.setInputValue(\({widgetId}_\){field}, envelope) call where envelope is the ShinyEnvelope&lt;T&gt; shape:
interface ShinyEnvelope&lt;T = unknown&gt; {
  value: T;             // the typed payload
  source: "user" | "proxy";  // provenance — see docs/dev/source-tagging.md
  ts: number;           // epoch ms at emission
}
See docs/dev/source-tagging.md for the full source-tag contract and rationale.

The aggregate _state bundle
The Shiny adapter listens to change and (after 150ms of inactivity) emits one combined input:
input$&lt;widgetId&gt;_state = ShinyEnvelope&lt;{
  sort, filters, row_styles, cell_styles, paint_tool, selected,
  collapsed_groups, hidden_columns, column_order, column_widths,
  cell_edits, label_edits, zoom, axis_zooms, banding, plot_width
}&gt;
Field names use snake_case (matching the individual wire fields) and values come from the current store state at flush time, not from the events. This means the bundle is always a consistent snapshot — there’s no risk of stale fields mixing with fresh ones.

Subscribing from non-Shiny consumers
When the eventual @tabviz/core ships (Phase 3), JS consumers subscribe directly:
const instance = createTabviz(element, spec);
instance.on("selected", (rowIds) =&gt; { /* ... */ });
instance.on("change", () =&gt; {
  // For non-Shiny consumers who want batched state — read the
  // current state from the instance whenever change fires, or
  // debounce yourself.
});
The payload types are exported from @tabviz/core/spec (the TabvizEvents interface in events.ts) so consumers get full type checking.

Method Dispatch
S7 methods are registered for generic functions:
# Print method for WebSpec
method(print, WebSpec) &lt;- function(x, ...) {
  cli_inform(c(
    "A {.cls WebSpec} with {nrow(x@data)} row{?s}",
    "*" = "Columns: {length(x@columns)}",
    "*" = "Groups: {length(x@groups)}"
  ))
  invisible(x)
}

# Plot method (renders as widget)
method(plot, WebSpec) &lt;- function(x, ...) {
  forest_plot(x, ...)
}

# as.data.frame method
method(as.data.frame, WebSpec) &lt;- function(x, ...) {
  x@data
}

knit_print for WebSpec / SplitForest
S7 class strings carry the pkg::Class prefix (e.g. "tabviz::WebSpec"), which can’t appear in R function names — so the standard knit_print.tabviz::SplitForest &lt;- pattern is illegal and @exportS3Method doesn’t help. Instead, plain handlers in R/forest_plot.R are bound to the raw class strings via registerS3method() in .onLoad:
# R/forest_plot.R
knit_print_splitforest &lt;- function(x, ...) {
  knitr::knit_print(forest_plot_split(x), ...)
}
knit_print_webspec &lt;- function(x, ...) {
  knitr::knit_print(render_tabviz_widget(x), ...)
}

# R/zzz.R — registered at package load time
registerS3method("knit_print", "tabviz::SplitForest",
                 knit_print_splitforest, envir = asNamespace("knitr"))
Without this binding, knitr’s auto-print fell back to S7’s default print on a chunk whose last value was a WebSpec or SplitForest — which dumped the object’s internal structure as raw &lt;pre&gt; text. The registered handlers route through forest_plot_split() / render_tabviz_widget() so chunks render as live widgets.

package_themes()
Returns a 2-level named list of every theme distributed with the package (journals and lotr) — handy for the enable_themes argument of web_interaction() or for iterating in tests. The nested shape is preserved by the in-widget switcher when you pass it through, producing a tabbed picker (one tab per category).
package_themes() |&gt; str(max.level = 2)
# List of 2
#  $ journals:List of 4
#   ..$ cochrane: &lt;WebTheme&gt;
#   ..$ lancet  : &lt;WebTheme&gt;
#   ..$ jama    : &lt;WebTheme&gt;
#   ..$ dark    : &lt;WebTheme&gt;
#  $ lotr    :List of 3
#   ..$ dwarven: &lt;WebTheme&gt;
#   ..$ elvish : &lt;WebTheme&gt;
#   ..$ hobbit : &lt;WebTheme&gt;

Type Checking Patterns

S7_inherits for Runtime Checks
# In modifiers.R
set_row_style &lt;- function(x, ...) {
  spec &lt;- if (inherits(x, "htmlwidget")) {
    attr(x, "webspec")
  } else if (S7_inherits(x, WebSpec)) {
    x
  } else {
    cli_abort("x must be a WebSpec or htmlwidget")
  }
  ...
}

# In columns.R
col_group &lt;- function(header, ...) {
  columns &lt;- list(...)
  for (i in seq_along(columns)) {
    if (!S7_inherits(columns[[i]], ColumnSpec)) {
      cli_abort("All arguments must be ColumnSpec objects")
    }
  }
  ...
}


class_any Escape Hatch
Some properties use class_any for flexibility:
# Allows NULL or WebTheme
theme = new_property(class_any, default = NULL)

# Allows numeric or "auto" string
width = new_property(class_any, default = NA_real_)

# Allows NULL or numeric vector
tick_values = new_property(class_any, default = NULL)
A more type-safe approach would use unions:
theme = new_property(
  new_union(WebTheme, class_missing),
  default = NULL
)

Method Dispatch
S7 methods are registered for generic functions:
# Print method for WebSpec
method(print, WebSpec) &lt;- function(x, ...) {
  cli_inform(c(
    "A {.cls WebSpec} with {nrow(x@data)} row{?s}",
    "*" = "Columns: {length(x@columns)}",
    "*" = "Groups: {length(x@groups)}"
  ))
  invisible(x)
}

# Plot method (renders as widget via forest_plot)
method(plot, WebSpec) &lt;- function(x, ...) {
  forest_plot(x, ...)
}

# as.data.frame method
method(as.data.frame, WebSpec) &lt;- function(x, ...) {
  x@data
}

Web Integration

DownloadButton.svelte
The download button calls the same generator directly:
import { exportToSVG, exportToPNG } from "$lib/export";

async function handleExportSVG() {
  const svgString = exportToSVG(store.spec);
  // Create blob and trigger download
}


export.ts
Thin wrapper around svg-generator:
import { generateSVG, svgToBlob } from "./svg-generator";

export function exportToSVG(spec: WebSpec): string {
  return generateSVG(spec);
}

export async function exportToPNG(spec: WebSpec, scale = 2): Promise&lt;Blob&gt; {
  const svgString = generateSVG(spec);
  return svgToBlob(svgString, scale);  // Render to canvas, export
}

